@{i}(C) 1997 Computermay@{ui}

@NODE Intro "Introduction "


Thanks a lot for trying my clock!!

This clock is something like a port from PC-Windoz of a little program I found once.

At this point you should be thinking... Bahh!! Another clock!!.Ok, but first read the features :

- Tells you the time (via samples).

- Chime every hour, quarter,etc...

- Fully configurable (via MUI).

- You can use your very own samples.

- Alarms (as much as you like).

- It can feed your pet ;).

@ENDNODE

@NODE Req "Requeriments"

- Amiga.
- MUI 3+.
- Ears, almost one sane ;).

@NODE Instalacion "Instalation"


@ENDNODE

@NODE Uso "Usage"



@{b}Preferences 
----------------@{ub}


@{i}Settings: @{ui}


- Samples path: The path for your samples ;)

- Say the time every: Time interval to say the hour and minutes.

- Chime every: Time interval to sound like a wallclock ;)


@{i}Alarms : @{ui}

Here you can define your alarms and the sample to play.
The "Loop" check means that the alarm will be playing until you press the
"Stop Alarm" button.
The alarms are also saved.


@{b}Making your own samples
----------------------------@{ub}


The samples must be in IFF 8svx format.

- You must create all the samples.

- The "20X,30X,..." samples are needed for some languages (eg.: spanish) but
  they're absolutely useless for others (eg.: english), in this case copy the
  20, 30, etc... samples over the 20X,30X,etc...






@ENDNODE

